Package phonebook.hashes

Class OrderedLinearProbingHashTable

java.lang.Object
phonebook.hashes.OpenAddressingHashTable
phonebook.hashes.OrderedLinearProbingHashTable
All Implemented Interfaces:
HashTable
public class OrderedLinearProbingHashTable extends OpenAddressingHashTable

OrderedLinearProbingHashTable is an Openly Addressed HashTable implemented with Ordered Linear Probing as its collision resolution strategy: every key collision is resolved by moving one address over, and the keys in the chain is in order. It suffer from the " clustering " problem: collision resolutions tend to cluster collision chains locally, making it hard for new keys to be inserted without collisions. QuadraticProbingHashTable is a HashTable that tries to avoid this problem, albeit sacrificing cache locality.

  • Method Details

    • put

      public String put(String key, String value)
      Inserts the pair <key, value> into this. The container should not allow for null keys and values, and we will test if you are throwing a IllegalArgumentException from your code if this method is given null arguments! It is important that we establish that no null entries can exist in our database because the semantics of get(String) and remove(String) are that they return null if, and only if, their key parameter is null. This method is expected to run in amortized constant time. Different from LinearProbingHashTable, the keys in the chain are in order. As a result, we might increase the cost of insertion and reduce the cost on search miss. One thing to notice is that, in soft deletion, we ignore the tombstone during the reordering of the keys in the chain. We will have some example in the writeup. Instances of OrderedLinearProbingHashTable will follow the writeup's guidelines about how to internally resize the hash table when the capacity exceeds 50%
      Parameters:
      key - The record's key.
      value - The record's value.
      Returns:
      The value added.
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - if either argument is null.

    • capacity

      public int capacity()
      Description copied from interface: HashTable
      Returns the capacity of this HashTable. In Separate Chaining, this is the total number of cells from which the lists begin. In Open Addressing methods, this method returns the size of the underlying array. As a consequence, in SeparateChainingHashTable, it's possible for HashTable.size() to return a value larger than this method. On the other hand, for Open Addressing methods like LinearProbingHashTable and QuadraticProbingHashTable, the value returned by this method is an upper bound on the value returned by HashTable.size().
      Returns:
      the number of cells in the table.
